[
    {
        "content": "<p>How is the Gonshor exponential map <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>exp</mi><mo>⁡</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\exp</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.625em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mop\">exp</span></span></span></span> defined? I haven't been able to find a simple and readable definition.</p>",
        "id": 560145796,
        "sender_full_name": "Violeta Hernández",
        "timestamp": 1764075105
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Ok so after rereading Wikipedia enough I get it. The stuff with <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">[</mo><mi>x</mi><msub><mo stretchy=\"false\">]</mo><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>n</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">[x]_{2n+1}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">[</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span><span class=\"mclose\"><span class=\"mclose\">]</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3011em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:0em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">2</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">n</span><span class=\"mbin mtight\">+</span><span class=\"mord mtight\">1</span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.2083em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> is more convoluted than I would have liked, but I get it</p>",
        "id": 560184102,
        "sender_full_name": "Violeta Hernández",
        "timestamp": 1764084216
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Should we do what mathlib does and define a complex exponential first?</p>",
        "id": 560193804,
        "sender_full_name": "Aaron Liu",
        "timestamp": 1764086477
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Is the surcomplex exponential even a thing?</p>",
        "id": 560194036,
        "sender_full_name": "Violeta Hernández",
        "timestamp": 1764086533
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Likely it is, but <br>\na) If it generalizes from the Gonshor exponential then the generalization isn't trivial<br>\nb) I don't think this is anywhere in the literature</p>",
        "id": 560194204,
        "sender_full_name": "Violeta Hernández",
        "timestamp": 1764086576
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I do really wish it exists, I wonder what stuff like cos(w) gives you</p>",
        "id": 560194291,
        "sender_full_name": "Violeta Hernández",
        "timestamp": 1764086597
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>ah, going in circles is certainly a problem</p>",
        "id": 560195801,
        "sender_full_name": "Aaron Liu",
        "timestamp": 1764086973
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Maybe you can take it mod 2pi i</p>",
        "id": 560196011,
        "sender_full_name": "Aaron Liu",
        "timestamp": 1764087036
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I wonder if there's some way to define surreal cosines and sines via Taylor series shenanigans that then gives an appropriate surcomplex exponential</p>",
        "id": 560197685,
        "sender_full_name": "Violeta Hernández",
        "timestamp": 1764087474
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>the Gonshor exponential feels like a hack though, you use not only the Taylor series expansion but the fact that exp(x+y) = exp(x) exp(y) and some monotonicity properties in order to define it</p>",
        "id": 560197939,
        "sender_full_name": "Violeta Hernández",
        "timestamp": 1764087542
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>if you can somehow do this with cosines it would be much worse</p>",
        "id": 560198020,
        "sender_full_name": "Violeta Hernández",
        "timestamp": 1764087560
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Actually, fun fact: for an infinitesimal input, you can evaluate a real Taylor series on the surreals unambiguously</p>",
        "id": 560199916,
        "sender_full_name": "Violeta Hernández",
        "timestamp": 1764088077
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>... actually, wait</p>",
        "id": 560202571,
        "sender_full_name": "Violeta Hernández",
        "timestamp": 1764088768
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Suppose S is a well-ordered subset of positive surreals. Denote by nS the pointwise sum of n copies of S. Conjecture: every surreal is in at most finitely many sets nS.</p>",
        "id": 560202943,
        "sender_full_name": "Violeta Hernández",
        "timestamp": 1764088862
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>(this implies that a real Taylor series on an infinitesimal input is well defined)</p>",
        "id": 560203361,
        "sender_full_name": "Violeta Hernández",
        "timestamp": 1764088945
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"459227\">Violeta Hernández</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/518132-combinatorial-games/topic/Gonshor.20exponential/near/560194291\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>I do really wish it exists, I wonder what stuff like cos(w) gives you</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>I think w is 2pi times an integer?</p>",
        "id": 560204199,
        "sender_full_name": "Aaron Liu",
        "timestamp": 1764089127
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Yes</p>",
        "id": 560204268,
        "sender_full_name": "Violeta Hernández",
        "timestamp": 1764089143
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>sort of? not really?</p>",
        "id": 560204313,
        "sender_full_name": "Violeta Hernández",
        "timestamp": 1764089159
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Does that mean 2pi is a rational number since w is also an integer</p>",
        "id": 560204422,
        "sender_full_name": "Aaron Liu",
        "timestamp": 1764089190
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>if a surreal cosine existed I imagine it'd be</p>\n<ul>\n<li>the value of the Taylor series for infinitesimal or real inputs </li>\n<li>one for pure infinite inputs</li>\n<li>whatever the cosine addition formula tells you for a mix of both</li>\n</ul>",
        "id": 560204747,
        "sender_full_name": "Violeta Hernández",
        "timestamp": 1764089277
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>likewise for the sine</p>",
        "id": 560204782,
        "sender_full_name": "Violeta Hernández",
        "timestamp": 1764089285
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>That sounds plausible I guess</p>",
        "id": 560205063,
        "sender_full_name": "Aaron Liu",
        "timestamp": 1764089365
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>does the Taylor series always give you a value?</p>",
        "id": 560205120,
        "sender_full_name": "Aaron Liu",
        "timestamp": 1764089378
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Wikipedia suggests that this is true for exp</p>",
        "id": 560205523,
        "sender_full_name": "Violeta Hernández",
        "timestamp": 1764089489
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>How are you summing it up?</p>",
        "id": 560205617,
        "sender_full_name": "Aaron Liu",
        "timestamp": 1764089514
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Seems too good to be true for an arbitrary Taylor series and infinitesimal</p>",
        "id": 560205662,
        "sender_full_name": "Violeta Hernández",
        "timestamp": 1764089524
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>(deleted)</p>",
        "id": 560205863,
        "sender_full_name": "Violeta Hernández",
        "timestamp": 1764089583
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"459227\">Violeta Hernández</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/518132-combinatorial-games/topic/Gonshor.20exponential/near/560202943\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Suppose S is a well-ordered subset of positive surreals. Denote by nS the pointwise sum of n copies of S. Conjecture: every surreal is in at most finitely many sets nS.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>You'd need this to be true, and also, for the union of all nS to be well-founded</p>",
        "id": 560205879,
        "sender_full_name": "Violeta Hernández",
        "timestamp": 1764089587
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"816344\">Aaron Liu</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/518132-combinatorial-games/topic/Gonshor.20exponential/near/560205617\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>How are you summing it up?</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Expand Conway forms, add like coefficients</p>",
        "id": 560205954,
        "sender_full_name": "Violeta Hernández",
        "timestamp": 1764089611
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>How are you expanding powers of infinite sums?</p>",
        "id": 560206139,
        "sender_full_name": "Aaron Liu",
        "timestamp": 1764089663
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Oh is that why you need the thing to be true</p>",
        "id": 560206276,
        "sender_full_name": "Aaron Liu",
        "timestamp": 1764089709
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>That's just the definition of multiplication for Hahn series</p>",
        "id": 560206297,
        "sender_full_name": "Violeta Hernández",
        "timestamp": 1764089713
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>wait you can multiply them</p>",
        "id": 560206348,
        "sender_full_name": "Aaron Liu",
        "timestamp": 1764089726
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>the thing needs to be true so you can add like terms and join them into a new Hahn series</p>",
        "id": 560206354,
        "sender_full_name": "Violeta Hernández",
        "timestamp": 1764089728
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>oh I think it's true</p>",
        "id": 560207105,
        "sender_full_name": "Aaron Liu",
        "timestamp": 1764089926
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>the thing is true</p>",
        "id": 560207139,
        "sender_full_name": "Aaron Liu",
        "timestamp": 1764089933
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>oh, why?</p>",
        "id": 560207725,
        "sender_full_name": "Violeta Hernández",
        "timestamp": 1764090088
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I'm completely stuck on this problem</p>",
        "id": 560214610,
        "sender_full_name": "Violeta Hernández",
        "timestamp": 1764092083
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"400289\">@Artie Khovanov</span> Is this a known thing? \"An infinitesimal Hahn series can be substituted into a real power series\"</p>",
        "id": 560214804,
        "sender_full_name": "Violeta Hernández",
        "timestamp": 1764092131
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Oh wait I'm really sorry, wrong person</p>",
        "id": 560215008,
        "sender_full_name": "Violeta Hernández",
        "timestamp": 1764092189
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"873350\">@Weiyi Wang</span></p>",
        "id": 560215054,
        "sender_full_name": "Violeta Hernández",
        "timestamp": 1764092200
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>(I was watchingthis thread just as I was mentioned <span aria-label=\"joy\" class=\"emoji emoji-1f602\" role=\"img\" title=\"joy\">:joy:</span>)</p>",
        "id": 560215291,
        "sender_full_name": "Weiyi Wang",
        "timestamp": 1764092264
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I think that is...true? If I understand what you mean correctly. By infintestimal, you mean the exponential of the leading term is positive, right</p>",
        "id": 560215643,
        "sender_full_name": "Weiyi Wang",
        "timestamp": 1764092378
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>wait...</p>",
        "id": 560215865,
        "sender_full_name": "Weiyi Wang",
        "timestamp": 1764092442
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>By infinitesimal I mean that the leading coefficient cx^r has r &lt; 0, i.e. that the Hahn series is in a positive Archimedean class (assuming we haven't flipped the direction of those)</p>",
        "id": 560216042,
        "sender_full_name": "Violeta Hernández",
        "timestamp": 1764092502
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I was using mathlib's definition where the leading term has the smallest r but I get your point</p>",
        "id": 560216182,
        "sender_full_name": "Weiyi Wang",
        "timestamp": 1764092553
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I think you probably need the leading r to also not be infinitesimal to other r that appears in the series?</p>",
        "id": 560216428,
        "sender_full_name": "Weiyi Wang",
        "timestamp": 1764092639
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>To give an example, let z = x^-1 + x^-2 + ... Then you can formally substitute exp(z) = 1 + x^-1 + 3/2 x^-2 + 13/6 x^-3 + ...</p>\n<p>The claim is that this works for any infinitesimal Hahn series z and any real Taylor series</p>",
        "id": 560217063,
        "sender_full_name": "Violeta Hernández",
        "timestamp": 1764092841
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>each power of the hahn series will raise its order. If this order tends to infinity, then we are good, as the coefficient of each term will be fixed after certain partial sum. If it doesn't tends to infinity, but eventually covers all terms we care about, then we are also fine, and we can set all other terms to 0</p>",
        "id": 560217188,
        "sender_full_name": "Weiyi Wang",
        "timestamp": 1764092882
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>if r is restricted to integers, this is fine, because it naturally goes to infinity</p>",
        "id": 560217297,
        "sender_full_name": "Weiyi Wang",
        "timestamp": 1764092929
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>What's the order? The largest exponent?</p>",
        "id": 560217404,
        "sender_full_name": "Violeta Hernández",
        "timestamp": 1764092966
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>yes (or the smallest in mathlib order)</p>",
        "id": 560217531,
        "sender_full_name": "Weiyi Wang",
        "timestamp": 1764093008
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>The case I am not sure about is when you have both ε and 1 in the exponent</p>",
        "id": 560218090,
        "sender_full_name": "Weiyi Wang",
        "timestamp": 1764093210
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"459227\">Violeta Hernández</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/518132-combinatorial-games/topic/Gonshor.20exponential/near/560207725\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>oh, why?</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>I realized my proof is wrong but surely it can be fixed</p>",
        "id": 560218190,
        "sender_full_name": "Aaron Liu",
        "timestamp": 1764093244
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>If your exponents are all (negative) ordinals then the claim is simple to prove as well, any given ordinal must be the sum of no more other ordinals than the sum of its base w coefficients</p>",
        "id": 560218457,
        "sender_full_name": "Violeta Hernández",
        "timestamp": 1764093335
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>presumably the case where you have exponents in different Archimedean classes kind of behaves like this</p>",
        "id": 560218606,
        "sender_full_name": "Violeta Hernández",
        "timestamp": 1764093378
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Can we do some model theory magic to change the exponents into ordinals</p>",
        "id": 560218660,
        "sender_full_name": "Aaron Liu",
        "timestamp": 1764093395
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>would be cool but i doubt it</p>",
        "id": 560218981,
        "sender_full_name": "Violeta Hernández",
        "timestamp": 1764093503
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>you can have very many exponents crammed into the same archimedean class</p>",
        "id": 560219096,
        "sender_full_name": "Violeta Hernández",
        "timestamp": 1764093540
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>You can have many ordinals crammed into the same archimedean class</p>",
        "id": 560219204,
        "sender_full_name": "Aaron Liu",
        "timestamp": 1764093576
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><del>How you evaluate a power series at (x^(-ε) + x^(-1+ε))? (following your convention that exponent goes downwards) The coefficient of x^(-1) feels undefined</del></p>",
        "id": 560221130,
        "sender_full_name": "Weiyi Wang",
        "timestamp": 1764094153
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=HahnSeries.SummableFamily.powers#doc\">docs#HahnSeries.SummableFamily.powers</a> is it true that we just need to change coefficients in this and we are good?</p>",
        "id": 560221979,
        "sender_full_name": "Weiyi Wang",
        "timestamp": 1764094435
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"873350\">Weiyi Wang</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/518132-combinatorial-games/topic/Gonshor.20exponential/near/560221130\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p><del>How you evaluate a power series at (x^(-ε) + x^(-1+ε))? (following your convention that exponent goes downwards) The coefficient of x^(-1) feels undefined</del></p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>the only term that will contribute to that coefficient is the square <span aria-label=\"slight smile\" class=\"emoji emoji-1f642\" role=\"img\" title=\"slight smile\">:slight_smile:</span></p>",
        "id": 560224586,
        "sender_full_name": "Violeta Hernández",
        "timestamp": 1764095202
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"873350\">Weiyi Wang</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/518132-combinatorial-games/topic/Gonshor.20exponential/near/560221979\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p><a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=HahnSeries.SummableFamily.powers#doc\">docs#HahnSeries.SummableFamily.powers</a> is it true that we just need to change coefficients in this and we are good?</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Oh yeah! That's basically it</p>",
        "id": 560224980,
        "sender_full_name": "Violeta Hernández",
        "timestamp": 1764095326
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Not at my computer rn, you happen to know what the proof idea is here?</p>",
        "id": 560225025,
        "sender_full_name": "Violeta Hernández",
        "timestamp": 1764095340
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I am reading it for the first time</p>",
        "id": 560225145,
        "sender_full_name": "Weiyi Wang",
        "timestamp": 1764095378
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>From what I can gather, it's an application of Higman's lemma</p>",
        "id": 560602552,
        "sender_full_name": "Violeta Hernández",
        "timestamp": 1764251507
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Which tracks, because this is the first time I ever read about Higman's lemma <span aria-label=\"sweat smile\" class=\"emoji emoji-1f605\" role=\"img\" title=\"sweat smile\">:sweat_smile:</span></p>",
        "id": 560602587,
        "sender_full_name": "Violeta Hernández",
        "timestamp": 1764251519
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>oh, it's a special case of Kruskal's tree theorem</p>",
        "id": 560603319,
        "sender_full_name": "Violeta Hernández",
        "timestamp": 1764251707
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>of TREE function fame</p>",
        "id": 560603342,
        "sender_full_name": "Violeta Hernández",
        "timestamp": 1764251712
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Oh of course this is proved in Siegel as well<br>\n<a href=\"/user_uploads/3121/pVwkuOKh9yYey8nb2jneYPQn/image.png\">image.png</a></p>\n<div class=\"message_inline_image\"><a href=\"/user_uploads/3121/pVwkuOKh9yYey8nb2jneYPQn/image.png\" title=\"image.png\"><img data-original-content-type=\"image/png\" data-original-dimensions=\"860x191\" src=\"/user_uploads/thumbnail/3121/pVwkuOKh9yYey8nb2jneYPQn/image.png/840x560.webp\"></a></div>",
        "id": 562390212,
        "sender_full_name": "Violeta Hernández",
        "timestamp": 1765172743
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Oh in fact you have an even stronger version<br>\n<a href=\"/user_uploads/3121/ArT_4Tkf4AXR-zoE7zWfNJxc/image.png\">image.png</a></p>\n<div class=\"message_inline_image\"><a href=\"/user_uploads/3121/ArT_4Tkf4AXR-zoE7zWfNJxc/image.png\" title=\"image.png\"><img data-original-content-type=\"image/png\" data-original-dimensions=\"1152x255\" src=\"/user_uploads/thumbnail/3121/ArT_4Tkf4AXR-zoE7zWfNJxc/image.png/840x560.webp\"></a></div>",
        "id": 562392125,
        "sender_full_name": "Violeta Hernández",
        "timestamp": 1765174122
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Ok wow so apparently this is how you show that surreal numbers are real-closed</p>",
        "id": 562392560,
        "sender_full_name": "Violeta Hernández",
        "timestamp": 1765174403
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I kinda expected that this would be some dark sorcery and not just applied Taylor series</p>",
        "id": 562392576,
        "sender_full_name": "Violeta Hernández",
        "timestamp": 1765174413
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><a href=\"/user_uploads/3121/K5S11tdsIDvwSGDfXFlOtEss/image.png\">image.png</a><br>\n<a href=\"/user_uploads/3121/1YkQNgVLRUycHHACGfxbM9NC/image.png\">image.png</a><br>\nScreenshotting for posterity</p>\n<div class=\"message_inline_image\"><a href=\"/user_uploads/3121/K5S11tdsIDvwSGDfXFlOtEss/image.png\" title=\"image.png\"><img data-original-content-type=\"image/png\" data-original-dimensions=\"1159x663\" src=\"/user_uploads/thumbnail/3121/K5S11tdsIDvwSGDfXFlOtEss/image.png/840x560.webp\"></a></div><div class=\"message_inline_image\"><a href=\"/user_uploads/3121/1YkQNgVLRUycHHACGfxbM9NC/image.png\" title=\"image.png\"><img data-original-content-type=\"image/png\" data-original-dimensions=\"1166x1007\" src=\"/user_uploads/thumbnail/3121/1YkQNgVLRUycHHACGfxbM9NC/image.png/840x560.webp\"></a></div>",
        "id": 562392775,
        "sender_full_name": "Violeta Hernández",
        "timestamp": 1765174541
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Looks like I guessed right and the proof for Puiseaux series generalises!</p>",
        "id": 562462800,
        "sender_full_name": "Artie Khovanov",
        "timestamp": 1765199461
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I think we can state this argument very generally (it also works for lifting ACFs).</p>",
        "id": 562463668,
        "sender_full_name": "Artie Khovanov",
        "timestamp": 1765199709
    },
